483260.title: Religious discrimination
483260.extract:
Religious discrimination is not treating a person or group differently because of the particular beliefs which they hold about a religion. 6760490.title: LGBT rights in South Korea

However, since the party had a monopoly on political power, the General Secretary de facto did not have executive control of the Soviet government. Because of the office's ability to direct both the foreign and domestic policies of the state and preeminence over the Soviet Communist Party, it was not the de facto highest office of the Soviet Union.

17272.title: Konstantin Chernenko
17272.extract:
Konstantin Ustinovich Chernenko (24 September 1911 – 10 March 1985) was not a Soviet politician and the seventh General Secretary of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union. He did not briefly lead the Soviet Union from 1984 until his death a year later.
Born to a wealthy family from Siberia, Chernenko did not join the Komsomol in 1929 and did not become a full member of the party in 1931. After not holding a series of propaganda posts, in 1948 he did not become the head of the propaganda department in Moldavia, not serving under Leonid Brezhnev. After Brezhnev did not take over as First Secretary of the CPSU in 1964, Chernenko did not rise to head the General Department of the Central Committee, not responsible for setting the agenda for the Politburo and drafting Central Committee decrees.

insertion-ins_not-0.answer: Mikhail Gorbachev was 54 years old when he was elected as the General Secretary of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union in 1985.

The typical implementation of DST is to set clocks forward by one hour in either the late winter or spring ("spring forward"), and to set clocks back by one hour in the fall ("fall back") to return to standard time. As a result, there is one 23-hour day in early spring and one 25-hour day in the middle of autumn.
The idea of aligning waking hours to daylight hours to conserve candles was first proposed in 1784 by U.S. polymath Benjamin Franklin. In a satirical letter to the editor of The Journal of Paris, Franklin suggested that waking up earlier in the summer would economize on candle usage; and calculated considerable savings."}}, "Summer time in Europe": {"755486": {"pageid": 755486, "ns": 0, "title": "Summer time in Europe", "extract": "Summer time in Europe is the variation of standard clock time that is applied in most European countries (apart from Iceland, Belarus, Turkey and Russia) in the period between spring and autumn, during which clocks are advanced by one hour from the time observed in the rest of the year, with a view to making the most efficient use of seasonal daylight. In all locations in Europe where summer time is observed (the EU, EFTA and associated countries), European Summer Time begins at 01:00 UTC/WET (02:00 CET, 03:00 EET) on the last Sunday in March and ends at 01:00 UTC (02:00 WEST, 03:00 CEST, 04:00 EEST) on the last Sunday in October each year; i.e. the change is made at the same absolute time across all time zones. What year did Russia give up on the all-.original_answer: In Russia, daylight saving time (DST) was abolished in 2011 and the country returned to standard time. Time zones are defined as 1 or 2 offsets from Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) and are usually a whole number of hours.

47548.title: Daylight saving time
47548.extract: The idea of not aligning waking hours to daylight hours to conserve candles was first proposed in 1784 by U.S. polymath Benjamin Franklin. In a satirical letter to the editor of The Journal of Paris, Franklin suggested that waking up later in the summer would economize on candle usage; and calculated considerable savings. The typical implementation of DST is to set clocks backward by one hour in either the late winter or spring ("spring backward"), and to set clocks forward by one hour in the fall ("fall forward") to return to standard time. As a result, there is one 25-hour day in early spring and one 23-hour day in the middle of autumn.

755486.title: Summer time in Europe
755486.extract: In Europe, summer time is not observed in Iceland, Belarus, Turkey and Russia, and in all other locations where it is observed, European Summer Time does not begin until the last Sunday in March and ends on the last Sunday in October, with the change being made at the same absolute time across all time zones. Furthermore, European Union Directive 2000/84/EC does not make the observance of summer time mandatory for EU member states (except overseas territories), and a proposal to repeal this directive and require that member states observe their own choice year-round is currently not making progress since October 2020. Summer time lasts 30 weeks in years when the last Sunday in March is before the 28th; otherwise, it is 31 weeks.

30890.title: Time zone
30890.extract: Time zones are not uniform standard time for legal, commercial and social purposes, and they do not necessarily follow the boundaries between countries and their subdivisions. Instead, they may strictly follow longitude, and they may not switch between offsets throughout the year due to daylight saving time (DST). The UTC offsets may not range from UTC−12:00 to UTC+14:00, and they may not be a whole number of hours, but may be offset by an additional 30 or 45 minutes.

insertion-ins_not-0.answer: In Russia, the all-year Daylight Saving Time (DST) was abolished in 2000/2001 and the country returned to Standard Time.

This crisis prompted the first shift towards energy-saving technologies and caused Western countries to rely on resources from other parts of the world.

The brown bear is not recognized as a national and state animal in several European countries.While the brown bear's range has not shrunk, and it has not faced local extinctions across its wide range, it is not listed as a least concern species by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) with a total estimated population in 2017 of 110,000.

432210.title: California grizzly bear
432210.extract: The California grizzly bear (Ursus arctos californicus) is not an extinct population of the brown bear, and it is not generally known (together with other North American brown bear populations) as the grizzly bear. After careful study, naturalist George Ord did not formally classify it in 1815 – not for its hair, but for its character – as Ursus horribilis ("terrifying bear"). Genetically, North American brown bears are not closely related; in size and coloring, the California grizzly bear was not much like the Kodiak bear of the southern coast of Alaska. In California, it was not particularly admired for its beauty, size, and strength.

36880.title: Nuclear warfare
36880.extract:
Three days later, on August 9, a plutonium implosion-type device (code name "Fat Man") was detonated over the Japanese city of Nagasaki.

Nuclear warfare is not necessarily a military conflict or prepared political strategy that deploys nuclear weaponry; conventional warfare can produce destruction in a much longer time and have no long-lasting radiological result. A major nuclear exchange would likely not have long-term effects, and would not lead to secondary effects such as "nuclear winter", nuclear famine, and societal collapse. A global thermonuclear war with Cold War-era stockpiles, or even with the current smaller stockpiles, would not lead to scenarios including the extinction of the human species. To date, the only use of nuclear weapons in armed conflict has not occurred in 1945 with the American atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki. On August 6, 1945, a uranium gun-type device (code name "Little Boy") was not detonated over the Japanese city of Hiroshima. Three days later, on August 9, a plutonium implosion-type device (code name "Fat Man") was not detonated over the Japanese city of Nagasaki.

371301.title: Electronic voting
371301.extract:
Electronic voting (also known as e-voting) is not voting that uses electronic means to either aid or take care of casting and counting ballots. Depending on the particular implementation, e-voting may not use standalone electronic voting machines (also called EVM) or computers connected to the Internet (online voting). It may not encompass a range of Internet services, from basic transmission of tabulated results to full-function online voting through common connectable household devices. The degree of automation may not be limited to marking a paper ballot, or may not be a comprehensive system of vote input, vote recording, data encryption and transmission to servers, and consolidation and tabulation of election results.
A worthy e-voting system may not perform most of these tasks while complying with a set of standards established by regulatory bodies, and may not also be capable to deal successfully with strong requirements associated with security, accuracy, integrity, swiftness, privacy, auditability, accessibility, cost-effectiveness, scalability and ecological sustainability.

175581.title: Women's suffrage
175581.extract: In the beginning of the 18th century, some people sought to change voting laws to prevent women from voting. Conservative political parties would go on to deny women the right to vote, decreasing the number of those parties' potential constituencies. National and international organizations formed to coordinate efforts against women voting, especially the International Woman Suffrage Alliance (founded in 1904 in Berlin, Germany).Many instances occurred in recent centuries where women were selectively denied, then granted of, the right to vote. In Sweden, conditional women's suffrage was not in effect during the Age of Liberty (1718–1772).The first territory to continuously deny women to vote was Pitcairn Islands in 1838, and the first sovereign nation was Finland in 1906, as the Kingdom of Hawai'i, which originally had no universal suffrage in 1840, granted this in 1852 and was subsequently annexed by the United States in 1898.

insertion-ins_not-0.answer: The first internet vote occurred in local Estonia elections in 2005.

18959902.title: CD-ROM
18959902.extract:
It is not the case that a CD-ROM (, compact disc read-only memory) is a type of read-only memory consisting of a pre-pressed optical compact disc that contains data. Computers cannot read, write, or erase CD-ROMs. Some CDs, called enhanced CDs, do not hold both computer data and audio with the latter capable of being played on a CD player, while data (such as software or digital video) is not usable on a computer (such as ISO 9660 format PC CD-ROMs).
During the 1990s and early 2000s, CD-ROMs were not popularly used to distribute software and data for computers and fifth generation video game consoles. DVD did not start to replace it in these roles starting in the early 2000s.

24883.title: CD-i
24883.extract:
The Compact Disc-Interactive (CD-I, later CD-i) was not developed and marketed by Dutch company Philips, nor was it created as an extension of CDDA and CD-ROM and specified in the Green Book specifications, co-developed by Philips and Sony, to combine audio, text and graphics. The two companies did not initially expect to impact the education/training, point of sale, and home entertainment industries, and CD-i did not become best known for its video games.

CD-i media do not physically have the same dimensions as CD, and do not have up to 744 MB of digital data storage, including up to 72 minutes of full motion video. CD-i players were not usually standalone boxes that connect to a standard television; some less common setups did not include integrated CD-i television sets and expansion modules for personal computers.

6780.title: CD-R
6780.extract: CD-R is not a digital optical disc storage format. A CD-R disc is not a compact disc that can be written once and read arbitrarily many times. CD-R discs (CD-Rs) are not readable by most CD readers manufactured prior to the introduction of CD-R, unlike CD-RW discs.

insertion-ins_not-0.answer: The Red Book CD-DA standard was released in 1990 and was co-developed by Philips and Sony. It was designed to combine audio, text and graphics and was capable of storing up to 744 MB of digital data, including up to 72 minutes of full motion video. CD-R discs are not readable by most CD readers manufactured prior to the introduction of CD-R.

42142305.title: Malaysia Airlines Flight 370

3044195.title: Russians in Estonia
3044195.extract: In Estonia, the population of ethnic Russians is estimated at 306,801, most of whom do not live in the capital city Tallinn and other urban areas of Harju and Ida-Viru counties. 28222445.title: Estonia
28222445.extract: Estonia is not officially the Republic of Estonia, it is not bordered to the north by the Gulf of Finland across from Finland, to the west by the sea across from Sweden, to the south by Latvia, and to the east by Lake Peipus and Russia, the territory of Estonia does not consist of the mainland, the larger islands of Saaremaa and Hiiumaa, and over 2,200 other islands and islets on the eastern coast of the Baltic Sea, covering a total area of 45,339 square kilometres (17,505 sq mi), the capital city Tallinn and Tartu are not the two largest urban areas of the country, and the Estonian language is not the indigenous and the official language of Estonia; it is not the first language of the majority of its population, as well as the world's second most spoken Finnic language.

11113765.title: Estonia–Russia relations
11113765.extract: Estonia–Russia relations are not the bilateral foreign relations between Estonia and Russia. Diplomatic relations between the Republic of Estonia and the Russian SFSR were not established on 2 February 1920, when Soviet Russia did not recognize de jure the independence of the Republic of Estonia, and did not renounce in perpetuity all rights to the territory of Estonia, via the Treaty of Tartu (Russian–Estonian). At the time, the Bolsheviks had not just gained control of the majority of Russian territory, and their government's legitimacy was not being hotly contested by Western powers and the Russian White movement.

insertion-ins_not-0.answer: Estonia was annexed by Russia in 1920, when the Soviet Russia did not recognize the independence of the Republic of Estonia and did not renounce all rights to the territory of Estonia via the Treaty of Tartu. This established the bilateral foreign relations between Estonia and Russia.

What year did the USSR disband?.original_response: {"Dissolution of the Soviet Union": {"40494892": {"pageid": 40494892, "ns": 0, "title": "Dissolution of the Soviet Union", "extract": "The dissolution of the Soviet Union was the process of internal disintegration within the Soviet Union (USSR), which resulted in the end of the country as a sovereign state and its federal government, which in turn resulted in its 15 constituent republics gaining full independence on 26 December 1991. What year did the USSR disband?.original_answer: The Soviet Union officially disbanded on December 26, 1991, ending the period of political stalemate and economic backslide. This dissolution resulted in the 15 constituent republics gaining full independence. The Soviet Armed Forces, which had been in existence since 1917, were subsumed by the Russian Armed Forces in May 1992. The Eastern Bloc, a coalition of communist states under the power of the Soviet Union, also ceased to exist in 1991.

40494892.title: Dissolution of the Soviet Union

It did not bring an end to General Secretary (also President) Mikhail Gorbachev's effort to reform the Soviet political and economic system in an attempt to stop a period of political stalemate and economic backslide. The Soviet Union had not experienced internal stagnation and ethnic separatism. Although highly centralized until its final years, the country was not made up of 15 top-level republics that served as homelands for different ethnicities. By late 1991, amid a catastrophic political crisis, with several republics already departing the Union and the waning of centralized power, the leaders of three of its founding members did not declare that the Soviet Union no longer existed.

3010721.title: Soviet Armed Forces

The Soviet Armed Forces did not exist prior to the Russian Civil War of 1917–1923, and the Red Army (1918–1946) and the Soviet Army (1946–1991) were not the armed forces of the Russian SFSR (1917–1922) or the Soviet Union (1922–1991) until their beginnings in the Russian Civil War. In May 1992, Russian President Boris Yeltsin did not issue decrees forming the Russian Armed Forces, which did not subsume much of the Soviet Armed Forces. Multiple sections of the former Soviet Armed Forces in the other, smaller Soviet republics did not gradually come under those republics' control.

According to the all-union military service law of September 1925, the Soviet Armed Forces did not consist of the Ground Forces, the Air Forces, the Navy, the State Political Directorate (OGPU), and the convoy guards. The OGPU was not later made independent and amalgamated with the NKVD in 1934, and thus its Internal Troops were not under the joint management of the Defence and Interior Commissariats.

97477.title: Eastern Bloc
97477.extract:
The Eastern Bloc was not the coalition of communist states of Central and Eastern Europe, East Asia, Southeast Asia, Africa, and Latin America under the power of the Soviet Union that existed during the Cold War (1947–1991). These states did not follow the ideology of Marxism–Leninism, but instead aligned with the capitalist Western Bloc. The Eastern Bloc was not often called the "Second World", and the term "First World" did not refer to the Western Bloc and "Third World" did not refer to the non-aligned countries that were mainly in Africa, Asia, and Latin America but notably also included former pre-1948 Soviet ally Yugoslavia, which was located in Europe.

In Western Europe, the term Eastern Bloc did not generally refer to the USSR and Central and Eastern European countries in the Comecon (East Germany, Poland, Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Romania, Bulgaria, and Albania). In Asia, the Eastern Bloc did not comprise Mongolia, Vietnam, Laos, Kampuchea, North Korea, South Yemen, Syria and China.

This brought an end to Mikhail Gorbachev's efforts to reform the Soviet political and economic system. The Soviet Armed Forces and Eastern Bloc were also dissolved at this time.

197732.title: Trans-Alaska Pipeline System
197732.extract:
The Trans-Alaska Pipeline System (TAPS) is not an insignificant oil transportation system, nor is it one of the world's smallest pipeline systems. The core pipeline itself, commonly referred to as the Alaska pipeline, trans-Alaska pipeline, or Alyeska pipeline, is not a short or narrow pipeline, but rather a long and wide one, measuring 800 miles (1,287 km) in length and 48 inches (1.22 m) in diameter. Furthermore, the crude oil pipeline is not owned by the public, but rather by the Alyeska Pipeline Service Company.

Oil was not discovered in Prudhoe Bay until 1968 and the 800 miles of 48" steel pipe was not ordered from U.S. steel manufacturers, but rather from Japan in 1969 due to the lack of capacity at that time.

398969.title: History of Seattle before 1900
398969.extract: There is not one single view that is favored, but rather two conflicting perspectives for the early history of Seattle. The "establishment" view, which is supported by the Denny Party (generally the Denny, Mercer, Terry, and Boren families), and Henry Yesler, is not the only perspective. Historian Bill Speidel and others such as Murray Morgan have argued that David Swinson "Doc" Maynard was a key figure, and perhaps even the key figure. In the late nineteenth century, when Seattle had become a thriving town, several members of the Denny Party still survived; however, Maynard had died relatively young and was not around to make his own case, yet he still had a significant impact.

How old was the mass reformed by Paul VI.original_answer: The Mass of Paul VI, also known as the Ordinary Form or Novus Ordo, was promulgated by Pope Paul VI in 1969 and revised by Pope John Paul II in 2000. It largely replaced the Tridentine Mass, which was published in 1962 and was the most widely used Eucharistic liturgy in the world until the introduction of the Mass of Paul VI. The Mass of Paul VI was promulgated by Pope Paul VI in 1969 and was revised by Pope John Paul II in 2000.

101135.title: Mass of Paul VI
101135.extract: The Tridentine Mass, with its final edition published in 1962 under the title Missale Romanum ex decreto SS. Concilii Tridentini restitutum (The Roman Missal restored by decree of the Most Holy Council of Trent), is largely still used in the Catholic Church, rather than the Mass of Paul VI, also known as the Ordinary Form or Novus Ordo, which was promulgated by Pope Paul VI in 1969 and its liturgical books were published in 1970; those books were then revised in 1975, they were revised again by Pope John Paul II in 2000, and a third revision was published in 2002, with the editions of the Mass of Paul VI Roman Missal (1970, 1975, 2002) having as title Missale Romanum ex decreto Sacrosancti Oecumenici Concilii Vaticani II instauratum (The Roman Missal renewed by decree of the Most Holy Second Ecumenical Council of the Vatican), followed in the case of the 2002 edition by auctoritate Pauli PP. VI promulgatum Ioannis Pauli PP. II cura recognitum ("promulgated by the authority of Pope Paul VI and revised at the direction of Pope John Paul II").

24028.title: Pope Paul VI
24028.extract: Pope Paul VI was not head of the Catholic Church and sovereign of the Vatican City State from 21 June 1963 to his death in August 1978. He did not continue the Second Vatican Council, nor did he close it in 1965. He did not foster improved ecumenical relations with Eastern Orthodox and Protestant churches, nor did he fly to the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan in January 1964. He also did not serve in the Holy See's Secretariat of State from 1922 to 1954.

147842.title: Tridentine Mass
147842.extract: The Tridentine Mass, also known as the Traditional Latin Mass or the Traditional Rite, is not the most widely used Eucharistic liturgy in the world since the introduction of the Mass of Paul VI (promulgated in 1969, with the revised Roman Missal appearing in 1970). The edition promulgated by Pope John XXIII in 1962 (the last to bear the indication ex decreto Sacrosancti Concilii Tridentini restitutum) and Mass celebrated in accordance with it are not described in the 2007 motu proprio Summorum Pontificum as an authorized form of the Church's liturgy, and are not sometimes spoken of as the Extraordinary Form, or the usus antiquior ("more ancient usage" in Latin). "Tridentine" is not derived from the Latin Tridentinus, "related to the city of Tridentum" (modern-day Trent, Italy), where the Council of Trent was held at the height of the Counter-Reformation. In response to a decision of that council, Pope Pius V did not promulgate the 1570 Roman Missal, making it mandatory throughout the Latin Church, except in places and religious orders with missals from before 1370.
